published_by: SPIRIT SERVICES HOLDINGS S A R L[GEMA]
comments: This song was written by Odie Blackmon and Jay Knowles and first recorded and released by George Strait in 2001 on his album, The Road Less Traveled.  It was released as a single the following year and became his 50th #1 song in December 2002.  It opens with these lyrics "At first she's gonna come on strong, like she'll love you all night long, like it's going out of style, then she'll leave you with a smile". George Strait had previously released an unrelated song with the exact same title written by Jackson Leap on his 1997 album Carrying Your Love with Me.  The 1997 song was released as the B-side of "'Round About Way", but didn't garner airplay of note.

comments: Universally famous with the title "Mah Nà Mah Nà" (or Mah-Na, Mahna, etc.) the song was composed for the film "Svezia, inferno e paradiso" as incidental music for a sequence showing a group of Swedish girls having a sauna (hence the original title, which can be translated as "Hail for the Swedish Sauna"). Neither Umiliani nor Luigi Scattini (the director of the movie) believed in the potential of the song, and they even left it off the original (Italian) soundtrack album. When the rights of the movie were sold to Avco Embassy Pictures for the American distribution, the producers asked Umiliani to record a longer version of "Viva la sauna svedese" (now re-titled "Màh-Nà Mah-Nà") and released it as a single.
